  "prompt": "Why do I have to tip the server?",
  "response": "Tipping servers is a common practice in many countries, particularly in the United States, for several reasons:\n\n1. **Wage Structure:** In many places, servers are paid a lower base wage than other types of workers because tipping is expected to supplement their income. In the U.S., for example, the federal minimum wage for tipped employees is significantly lower than for non-tipped employees.\n\n2. **Service Quality Incentive:** Tipping is seen as a way to reward good service. It incentivizes servers to provide attentive and high-quality service to guests.\n\n3. **Cultural Norm:** Tipping has become a cultural norm in many societies. Not tipping or tipping inadequately might be seen as discourteous or disrespectful.\n\n4. **Shared Tips:** Tips often contribute to a pool that might be shared among other staff, such as bussers, bartenders, and hosts, who all play a part in your dining experience.\n\n5. **Economic Impact:** Many restaurants operate on thin margins and keeping menu prices competitive can be challenging. Relying on tips helps manage labor costs.\n\n6. **Show Appreciation:** Tipping is a direct way to show appreciation for the hard work and effort that servers put into their job, which can often be fast-paced and stressful.\n\nIn countries where tipping is not customary, servers are typically paid a full wage that doesn\u2019t rely on tips, and service charges may be included in the bill. It's always a good idea to familiarize yourself with the tipping practices of the place you are in to ensure you are following local customs and expectations.",
